          "body": "Genesis 16 opens with a sentence that has summarized the ache of countless lives: 'Sarai had borne him no children' (16:1). The problem is not Sarai's fault, not Abram's fault, and — as the chapter's theological framing insists — not even a sign of divine absence. God had promised Abram a great nation (12:2), had confirmed it with a blood-covenant (15:18), and had counted the stars as a pledge (15:5). None of that had produced a child. Ten years of waiting (16:3) had accumulated, and Sarai's proposed solution draws on accepted ancient Near Eastern custom: the Code of Hammurabi and Nuzi tablets from the mid-second millennium attest that a barren wife could give her handmaid as a surrogate wife, and the resulting child would be legally the mistress's. The scheme was culturally plausible. That is exactly what makes it a test. Faith is not tested by implausible temptations; it is tested when the alternative to waiting on God looks reasonable, respectable, and — above all — expedient. Sarai's move is the first recorded fulfillment of the principle James will codify two millennia later: desire, when it conceives, gives birth to action that bypasses God."
