        "range": "16:1-3",
        "excerpt": "So Sarai said to Abram, 'Now behold, the LORD has prevented me from bearing children. Please go in to my maid; perhaps I will obtain children through her.' And Abram listened to the voice of Sarai.",
        "body": "The chapter's first three verses compress a decade of anguish into a single proposal. Sarai's reasoning follows a recognizable pattern: she correctly identifies God as the one who controls fertility ('the LORD has prevented me,' 16:2), and then immediately uses that theological premise to justify taking control herself. The logic is not atheism but impatience dressed as theology: since God has done this, I will undo it. The ancient Near Eastern legal custom she invokes — the Nuzi tablets and Hammurabi's Code both attest surrogate-wife arrangements for barren wives — gave the scheme cultural cover. It was not lawless; it was merely faithless.\n\nAbram's compliance is the moral crisis of the passage. Verse 2 closes: 'Abram listened to the voice of Sarai.' Every careful reader of Genesis has heard that phrase before — Genesis 3:17 uses the same construction when God rebukes Adam: 'because you have listened to the voice of your wife.' The narrator is not making a misogynistic point about wives; he is making a typological point about the structure of faith-failure. The man entrusted with the promise deferred to the voice of expedient fear rather than to the silent patience of the covenant God. The result in both cases (Eden and Canaan) is an action taken outside the will of God that produces consequences spanning generations.\n\nVerse 3 closes the panel with a legal formality: 'Sarai took Hagar... and gave her to her husband Abram as his wife.' The deliberateness of the language — took, gave, as his wife — marks the transaction as intentional and irreversible. This is not a momentary lapse; it is a considered decision. Ten years of waiting had congealed into a strategy. The tragedy is not that Sarai and Abram were wicked; it is that they were normal. They did what reasonable, grieving people do when God seems to have forgotten. They helped.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Atsar* (16:2 — 'has prevented me') is the verb for restraining or shutting up; used of God closing Hannah's womb in 1 Samuel 1:5-6. Sarai's use of it is theologically accurate and self-serving simultaneously. *Banah* ('I will obtain children,' literally 'I will be built') echoes the ancient sense that a woman's legacy was 'built' through children — the same root underlies the word for 'son' (*ben*) and 'house/household' (*bayit*). The word choice makes her motivation nakedly existential."
